## Module 2: Advanced Type System Deep Dive

TypeScript’s type system is one of its most powerful features, enabling you to write safer, more expressive code by catching errors at compile time and providing fine-grained control over types. While basic types like `string`, `number`, and `boolean` are essential, TypeScript’s advanced type system offers even more depth and flexibility. In this chapter, we’ll explore some of the most impactful advanced features: **union and intersection types**, **discriminated unions**, **type guards**, **type assertions**, the `unknown` type, and **mapped, conditional, and recursive types**.

By mastering these concepts, you'll be able to model complex data structures, enforce stricter contracts, and write code that is both robust and maintainable.

---

## 1. Union and Intersection Types

### Union Types

Union types allow a variable to hold values of multiple types. You define them using the `|` (pipe) symbol.

```typescript
type StringOrNumber = string | number;

function printId(id: StringOrNumber) {
  console.log(`ID: ${id}`);
}

printId("abc123"); // Valid
printId(42);       // Valid
printId(true);     // Error: boolean is not assignable to StringOrNumber
```

In the example above, `printId` accepts either a `string` or a `number`. This is useful when a function can handle multiple input types.

### Intersection Types

Intersection types combine multiple types into one, requiring a value to satisfy all constituent types. Use the `&` (ampersand) symbol.

```typescript
interface Person {
  name: string;
  age: number;
}

interface Employee {
  id: string;
  department: string;
}

type EmployeePerson = Person & Employee;

const john: EmployeePerson = {
  name: "John Doe",
  age: 30,
  id: "EMP123",
  department: "Engineering",
};
```

Here, `EmployeePerson` is the intersection of `Person` and `Employee`. An object must have all fields from both interfaces to be of type `EmployeePerson`.

> **Tip**: Use intersection types to model objects that must satisfy multiple interfaces or type contracts.

---

## 2. Discriminated Unions

Discriminated unions (also known as tagged unions) are a pattern where a union type is distinguished by a common property—usually a `kind` or `type` field.

### Example: Shape Hierarchy

```typescript
type Shape =
  | { kind: "circle"; radius: number }
  | { kind: "rectangle"; width: number; height: number };

function area(shape: Shape): number {
  switch (shape.kind) {
    case "circle":
      return Math.PI * shape.radius ** 2;
    case "rectangle":
      return shape.width * shape.height;
    default:
      // Exhaustiveness check
      const _exhaustiveCheck: never = shape;
      return _exhaustiveCheck;
  }
}

console.log(area({ kind: "circle", radius: 5 })); // ~78.54
console.log(area({ kind: "rectangle", width: 4, height: 6 })); // 24
```

> **Why it matters**: Discriminated unions make your code self-documenting and enable the TypeScript compiler to perform **exhaustiveness checking**, ensuring all cases are handled.

---

## 3. Type Guards and Type Assertions

### Type Guards

Type guards are expressions that perform runtime checks to narrow down types. TypeScript uses these to infer more specific types within a conditional block.

```typescript
function isString(value: unknown): value is string {
  return typeof value === "string";
}

function logValue(value: unknown) {
  if (isString(value)) {
    console.log(value.toUpperCase()); // Safe: value is string
  } else {
    console.log("Not a string");
  }
}

logValue("hello"); // "HELLO"
logValue(123);     // "Not a string"
```

> The `value is string` return type is a **type predicate**, telling TypeScript that if the function returns `true`, `value` is definitely a `string`.

### Type Assertions

Type assertions are a way to tell TypeScript, "I know more about this type than you do." Use the `as` keyword or `<Type>` syntax.

```typescript
interface User {
  id: number;
  name: string;
}

const data: unknown = { id: 1, name: "Alice" };

// Without assertion, we can't access properties
// console.log(data.name); // Error

// Safe: We assert it's a User
const user = data as User;
console.log(user.name); // "Alice"
```

> ⚠️ **Caution**: Type assertions bypass type checking. Use them only when you're certain about the type at runtime.

---

## 4. The `unknown` Type

The `unknown` type represents any value. It’s safer than `any` because you must perform type checks before using the value.

```typescript
let value: unknown = "Hello";

if (typeof value === "string") {
  console.log(value.toUpperCase()); // Safe
}

// value.toUpperCase(); // Error: Object is of type 'unknown'
```

> **Best Practice**: Prefer `unknown` over `any` when dealing with external data (e.g., API responses) to enforce type safety.

---

## 5. Mapped Types

Mapped types allow you to create new types by transforming properties of existing types.

```typescript
type Optional<T> = {
  [K in keyof T]?: T[K];
};

interface User {
  id: number;
  name: string;
  email: string;
}

type PartialUser = Optional<User>;
// Equivalent to: { id?: number; name?: string; email?: string }
```

> **Use Case**: Create utility types like `Partial`, `Readonly`, `Record`, and `Pick` rely on mapped types.

---

## 6. Conditional Types

Conditional types allow types to be chosen based on conditions, similar to ternary operators in JavaScript.

```typescript
type NonNullable<T> = T extends null | undefined ? never : T;

type A = NonNullable<string | null>; // string
type B = NonNullable<null | undefined>; // never
```

```typescript
type IsString<T> = T extends string ? true : false;

type C = IsString<"hello">; // true
type D = IsString<42>;      // false
```

> **Advanced Use**: Conditional types power many built-in utilities like `Extract` and `Exclude`.

---

## 7. Recursive Types

Recursive types allow types to reference themselves, enabling the modeling of nested or tree-like structures.

### Example: JSON Tree

```typescript
type Json =
  | string
  | number
  | boolean
  | null
  | Json[]
  | { [key: string]: Json };

function parseJson(json: Json) {
  // Recursively process JSON data
  if (Array.isArray(json)) {
    json.forEach(item => parseJson(item));
  } else if (typeof json === "object" && json !== null) {
    Object.values(json).forEach(value => parseJson(value));
  }
  return json;
}
```

> Recursive types are essential for modeling deeply nested data like configuration objects, ASTs, or tree structures.

---

## Real-World Example: Form State Management

Let’s combine several advanced types to model a dynamic form state:

```typescript
type FormField<T> =
  | { value: T; error: string | null }
  | { value: null; error: string };

type FormState<T> = {
  [K in keyof T]: FormField<T[K]>;
};

interface LoginForm {
  email: string;
  password: string;
}

const form: FormState<LoginForm> = {
  email: { value: "user@example.com", error: null },
  password: { value: null, error: "Password is required" },
};
```

This structure allows for flexible form state management where fields can be valid, invalid, or empty, all while maintaining type safety.

---

## Summary

TypeScript’s advanced type system is not just an academic feature—it’s a practical toolkit for modeling real-world problems with precision. By leveraging **union and intersection types**, you can express complex data relationships. **Discriminated unions** bring clarity and safety to branching logic. **Type guards** and **type assertions** bridge the gap between static types and dynamic data. The `unknown` type enforces discipline when dealing with external inputs. And with **mapped**, **conditional**, and **recursive types**, you can build reusable, scalable type utilities that grow with your application.

These features elevate your code from "works" to "correct"—and from "correct" to "self-documenting, maintainable, and future-proof."

---

## Key Takeaways

- **Union types** (`A | B`) allow a variable to be one of several types; **intersection types** (`A & B`) require all types simultaneously.
- **Discriminated unions** use a common property to distinguish types, enabling exhaustive checks and cleaner switch logic.
- **Type guards**, **type assertions**, and the `unknown` type help safely handle dynamic or ambiguous data while preserving type safety.

## Module 3: Object-Oriented Programming in TypeScript

Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) is a fundamental paradigm that enables developers to structure code in a modular, reusable, and scalable way. TypeScript, with its strong typing and class-based syntax, makes OOP not only possible but highly effective. In this module, we'll explore how to use classes, interfaces, access modifiers, and SOLID principles to write robust, maintainable TypeScript applications.

---

## Classes: The Building Blocks of OOP

A **class** in TypeScript is a blueprint for creating objects. It encapsulates data (properties) and behavior (methods) into a single unit. Unlike JavaScript's prototype-based inheritance, TypeScript classes provide a cleaner, more intuitive syntax.

### Defining a Class

```typescript
class Person {
    // Properties
    name: string;
    age: number;

    // Constructor
    constructor(name: string, age: number) {
        this.name = name;
        this.age = age;
    }

    // Method
    greet(): void {
        console.log(`Hello, I'm ${this.name} and I'm ${this.age} years old.`);
    }
}

// Usage
const alice = new Person("Alice", 30);
alice.greet(); // Output: Hello, I'm Alice and I'm 30 years old.
```

### Access Modifiers

TypeScript supports **access modifiers** to control the visibility of class members:

- `public`: Accessible anywhere (default).
- `private`: Accessible only within the class.
- `protected`: Accessible within the class and its subclasses.

```typescript
class Employee {
    private id: string;
    public name: string;
    protected salary: number;

    constructor(id: string, name: string, salary: number) {
        this.id = id; // Private
        this.name = name; // Public
        this.salary = salary; // Protected
    }

    public getSalary(): number {
        return this.salary;
    }

    private logId(): void {
        console.log(`Employee ID: ${this.id}`);
    }
}

const emp = new Employee("E123", "Bob", 50000);
console.log(emp.name); // OK: Public
console.log(emp.getSalary()); // OK: Public method
// console.log(emp.salary); // Error: Protected
// emp.logId(); // Error: Private
```

---

## Interfaces: Contracts for Objects

Interfaces define the **shape** of an object—what properties and methods it must have—without implementing them. They are crucial for **dependency injection** and ensuring type safety.

### Defining and Implementing an Interface

```typescript
interface ILogger {
    log(message: string): void;
    error(message: string): void;
}

class ConsoleLogger implements ILogger {
    log(message: string): void {
        console.log(`[LOG] ${message}`);
    }

    error(message: string): void {
        console.error(`[ERROR] ${message}`);
    }
}

class FileLogger implements ILogger {
    log(message: string): void {
        // Simulate writing to a file
        console.log(`[FILE LOG] ${message}`);
    }

    error(message: string): void {
        console.error(`[FILE ERROR] ${message}`);
    }
}

// Dependency Injection
function logError(logger: ILogger, message: string): void {
    logger.error(message);
}

const consoleLogger = new ConsoleLogger();
const fileLogger = new FileLogger();

logError(consoleLogger, "Something went wrong!"); // Output: [ERROR] Something went wrong!
logError(fileLogger, "Critical failure!"); // Output: [FILE ERROR] Critical failure!
```

In this example, `logError` accepts any object that implements `ILogger`, allowing flexible logging strategies without tight coupling.

---

## Abstract Classes: Partial Implementations

An **abstract class** is a class that cannot be instantiated directly and may contain **abstract methods** (methods without implementation). It serves as a base class for other classes.

### Defining an Abstract Class

```typescript
abstract class Animal {
    abstract makeSound(): void; // Abstract method

    move(): void {
        console.log("The animal moves.");
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    makeSound(): void {
        console.log("Woof!");
    }
}

class Cat extends Animal {
    makeSound(): void {
        console.log("Meow!");
    }
}

const dog = new Dog();
dog.makeSound(); // Output: Woof!
dog.move(); // Output: The animal moves.

// const animal = new Animal(); // Error: Cannot create an instance of an abstract class.
```

Abstract classes are useful when you want to define a common interface while allowing subclasses to provide specific implementations.

---

## SOLID Principles in TypeScript

The **SOLID** principles are a set of five design principles that help create maintainable and scalable software. Let's see how they apply in TypeScript.

### 1. Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)

*A class should have only one reason to change.*

**Bad Example:**
```typescript
class User {
    constructor(public name: string, public email: string) {}

    saveToDatabase(): void {
        console.log(`Saving ${this.name} to database...`);
    }

    sendEmail(subject: string, message: string): void {
        console.log(`Sending email to ${this.email}: ${subject}`);
    }
}
```
This class handles both data persistence and email sending, violating SRP.

**Good Example:**
```typescript
class User {
    constructor(public name: string, public email: string) {}
}

class UserRepository {
    save(user: User): void {
        console.log(`Saving ${user.name} to database...`);
    }
}

class EmailService {
    send(to: string, subject: string, message: string): void {
        console.log(`Sending email to ${to}: ${subject}`);
    }
}
```

### 2. Open/Closed Principle (OCP)

*Classes should be open for extension but closed for modification.*

**Bad Example:**
```typescript
class Discount {
    giveDiscount(customerType: string): number {
        if (customerType === "regular") return 0.1;
        if (customerType === "premium") return 0.2;
        return 0;
    }
}
```
Adding a new customer type requires modifying the `Discount` class.

**Good Example:**
```typescript
interface CustomerType {
    discount(): number;
}

class RegularCustomer implements CustomerType {
    discount(): number {
        return 0.1;
    }
}

class PremiumCustomer implements CustomerType {
    discount(): number {
        return 0.2;
    }
}

class Discount {
    giveDiscount(customer: CustomerType): number {
        return customer.discount();
    }
}
```
New customer types can be added without changing the `Discount` class.

### 3. Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP)

*Subtypes must be substitutable for their base types.*

**Bad Example:**
```typescript
class Rectangle {
    constructor(public width: number, public height: number) {}

    setWidth(width: number): void {
        this.width = width;
    }

    setHeight(height: number): void {
        this.height = height;
    }

    area(): number {
        return this.width * this.height;
    }
}

class Square extends Rectangle {
    setWidth(width: number): void {
        this.width = width;
        this.height = width; // Violates LSP: Square's width and height must be equal
    }

    setHeight(height: number): void {
        this.height = height;
        this.width = height;
    }
}

function printArea(rectangle: Rectangle): void {
    rectangle.setWidth(5);
    rectangle.setHeight(4);
    console.log(rectangle.area()); // Expected: 20, but Square returns 16
}
```
A `Square` cannot substitute a `Rectangle` without breaking behavior.

**Good Example:**
```typescript
interface Shape {
    area(): number;
}

class Rectangle implements Shape {
    constructor(public width: number, public height: number) {}

    area(): number {
        return this.width * this.height;
    }
}

class Square implements Shape {
    constructor(public side: number) {}

    area(): number {
        return this.side * this.side;
    }
}

function printArea(shape: Shape): void {
    console.log(shape.area());
}
```
Now, any `Shape` can be substituted without issues.

---

## Real-World Example: E-Commerce Order System

Let's apply OOP principles to an e-commerce order system.

```typescript
// Interfaces
interface IOrder {
    calculateTotal(): number;
}

interface IPaymentProcessor {
    processPayment(amount: number): boolean;
}

// Abstract Class
abstract class OrderBase implements IOrder {
    constructor(
        protected items: { name: string; price: number; quantity: number }[],
        protected paymentProcessor: IPaymentProcessor
    ) {}

    abstract calculateTotal(): number;

    processPayment(): boolean {
        const total = this.calculateTotal();
        return this.paymentProcessor.processPayment(total);
    }
}

// Concrete Classes
class StandardOrder extends OrderBase {
    calculateTotal(): number {
        return this.items.reduce(
            (sum, item) => sum + item.price * item.quantity,
            0
        );
    }
}

class PremiumOrder extends OrderBase {
    calculateTotal(): number {
        const subtotal = this.items.reduce(
            (sum, item) => sum + item.price * item.quantity,
            0
        );
        return subtotal * 0.9; // 10% discount
    }
}

// Payment Processors
