## 2. Dependency Injection & Inversion of Control

**Dependency Injection (DI)** is a design pattern that promotes **Inversion of Control (IoC)** by delegating the responsibility of providing dependencies to an external system (like a container).

### Why Use DI?
- Improves testability.
- Reduces tight coupling.
- Enhances maintainability and reusability.

### Example: DI in a User Service

```typescript
// Define interfaces
interface UserRepository {
  findById(id: string): User | null;
}

interface Logger {
  log(message: string): void;
}

// Concrete implementations
class InMemoryUserRepository implements UserRepository {
  private users = new Map<string, User>();

  findById(id: string): User | null {
    return this.users.get(id) || null;
  }

  addUser(user: User) {
    this.users.set(user.id, user);
  }
}

class ConsoleLogger implements Logger {
  log(message: string): void {
    console.log(`[LOG] ${message}`);
  }
}

// User model
class User {
  constructor(public id: string, public name: string) {}
}

// UserService depends on abstractions
class UserService {
  constructor(
    private userRepo: UserRepository,
    private logger: Logger
  ) {}

  getUser(id: string): User | null {
    this.logger.log(`Fetching user with ID: ${id}`);
    return this.userRepo.findById(id);
  }
}

// External Composition Root (DI Container)
class AppContainer {
  private static userRepo: UserRepository;
  private static logger: Logger;

  static init() {
    this.userRepo = new InMemoryUserRepository();
    this.logger = new ConsoleLogger();

    // Register users
    (this.userRepo as InMemoryUserRepository).addUser(
      new User("1", "Alice")
    );
  }

  static resolveUserService(): UserService {
    return new UserService(this.userRepo, this.logger);
  }
}

// Bootstrap the application
AppContainer.init();
const userService = AppContainer.resolveUserService();

// Use the service
const user = userService.getUser("1");
console.log(user?.name); // Output: "Alice"
```

> 🔁 **IoC Principle**: Instead of the `UserService` creating its dependencies, they are "injected" from the outside. This makes it easy to swap implementations (e.g., switch to a database-based repository during testing).

