# Chapter 6: Module 6: Advanced Patterns & Design Techniques

## Module 6: Advanced Patterns & Design Techniques

Welcome to **Module 6** of *Learn TypeScript for Professional Development*. In this chapter, we’ll explore advanced design patterns and techniques that professional developers use to write scalable, maintainable, and robust TypeScript applications. You’ll learn how to implement **Factory**, **Singleton**, and **Decorator** patterns, apply **Dependency Injection (DI)** and **Inversion of Control (IoC)**, and leverage the **Visitor Pattern** for complex type transformations.

By the end of this module, you’ll be equipped with powerful architectural tools that will elevate your TypeScript code to enterprise-level standards.

---

## 1. Implementing Design Patterns in TypeScript

Design patterns are reusable solutions to common problems in software design. In TypeScript, these patterns help manage complexity, improve code organization, and ensure type safety. Let’s dive into three essential patterns.

---

### 1.1 The Factory Pattern

The **Factory Pattern** is a creational pattern that provides an interface for creating objects in a superclass, but allows subclasses to alter the type of objects that will be created. It promotes loose coupling by eliminating the need to bind application-specific classes into the code.

#### When to Use:
- When you don’t know beforehand the exact types and dependencies of the objects your code should work with.
- When you want to provide users of your library or framework with a way to extend internal components.
- To encapsulate complex object creation logic.

#### Example: Creating UI Components

```typescript
// Define a base interface for UI components
interface UIComponent {
  render(): void;
  getType(): string;
}

// Concrete components
class Button implements UIComponent {
  render() {
    console.log("Rendering a Button");
  }
  getType() {
    return "Button";
  }
}

class Modal implements UIComponent {
  render() {
    console.log("Rendering a Modal");
  }
  getType() {
    return "Modal";
  }
}

// Factory interface
interface UIFactory {
  createComponent(type: string): UIComponent | null;
}

// Concrete factory
class UIComponentFactory implements UIFactory {
  createComponent(type: string): UIComponent | null {
    switch (type.toLowerCase()) {
      case "button":
        return new Button();
      case "modal":
        return new Modal();
      default:
        console.warn(`Unknown component type: ${type}`);
        return null;
    }
  }
}

// Usage
const factory = new UIComponentFactory();

const button = factory.createComponent("button");
button?.render(); // Output: "Rendering a Button"

const modal = factory.createComponent("modal");
modal?.render(); // Output: "Rendering a Modal"
```

> 💡 **Pro Tip**: Use TypeScript’s discriminated unions and type guards to enhance factory safety. You can extend the factory to return a union type like `Button | Modal | null` and use `instanceof` or custom type guards to validate.

---

### 1.2 The Singleton Pattern

The **Singleton Pattern** ensures that a class has only one instance and provides a global point of access to it. It’s useful for managing shared resources like configuration, logging, or database connections.

#### When to Use:
- When exactly one object is needed to coordinate actions across the system.
- For managing resources like configuration settings or logging services.

#### Example: Application Configuration Manager

```typescript
class AppConfig {
  private static instance: AppConfig | null = null;
  private settings: Record<string, any> = {};

  // Private constructor to prevent direct instantiation
  private constructor() {}

  // Public static method to get the instance
  public static getInstance(): AppConfig {
    if (!AppConfig.instance) {
      AppConfig.instance = new AppConfig();
    }
    return AppConfig.instance;
  }

  // Prevent cloning
  public clone(): never {
    throw new Error("Cloning of singleton is not allowed.");
  }

  // Prevent reinitialization
  public reset(): never {
    throw new Error("Cannot reset singleton instance.");
  }

  // Add configuration methods
  public setSetting(key: string, value: any): void {
    this.settings[key] = value;
  }

  public getSetting<T>(key: string): T {
    return this.settings[key] as T;
  }
}

// Usage
const config1 = AppConfig.getInstance();
config1.setSetting("apiUrl", "https://api.example.com");

const config2 = AppConfig.getInstance();
console.log(config2.getSetting<string>("apiUrl")); // Output: "https://api.example.com"

// Both variables reference the same instance
console.log(config1 === config2); // Output: true
```

> ⚠️ **Caveat**: While singletons are useful, overuse can lead to tight coupling and make testing difficult. Prefer dependency injection where possible.

---

### 1.3 The Decorator Pattern

The **Decorator Pattern** allows behavior to be added to an individual object dynamically, without affecting the behavior of other objects from the same class. It provides a flexible alternative to subclassing for extending functionality.

#### When to Use:
- To add responsibilities to objects dynamically.
- When inheritance would result in an explosion of subclasses.

#### Example: Logging Middleware for HTTP Requests

```typescript
// Base interface
interface RequestHandler {
  handle(request: string): string;
}

// Concrete component
class BaseRequestHandler implements RequestHandler {
  handle(request: string): string {
    return `Processed: ${request}`;
  }
}

// Abstract decorator
abstract class RequestHandlerDecorator implements RequestHandler {
  protected constructor(protected handler: RequestHandler) {}

  abstract handle(request: string): string;
}

// Concrete decorator: Logging
class LoggingDecorator extends RequestHandlerDecorator {
  handle(request: string): string {
    console.log(`[LOG] Request received: ${request}`);
    return this.handler.handle(request);
  }
}

// Concrete decorator: Timing
class TimingDecorator extends RequestHandlerDecorator {
  handle(request: string): string {
    const start = performance.now();
    const result = this.handler.handle(request);
    const end = performance.now();
    console.log(`[TIMING] Request processed in ${end - start} ms`);
    return result;
  }
}

// Usage
let handler: RequestHandler = new BaseRequestHandler();
handler = new LoggingDecorator(handler);
handler = new TimingDecorator(handler);

const response = handler.handle("GET /users");
console.log(response);
// Output:
// [LOG] Request received: GET /users
// [TIMING] Request processed in X ms
// Processed: GET /users
```

> ✅ **Benefit**: Decorators allow you to stack behaviors dynamically, making your code more modular and reusable.

---

## 2. Dependency Injection & Inversion of Control

**Dependency Injection (DI)** is a design pattern that promotes **Inversion of Control (IoC)** by delegating the responsibility of providing dependencies to an external system (like a container).

### Why Use DI?
- Improves testability.
- Reduces tight coupling.
- Enhances maintainability and reusability.

### Example: DI in a User Service

```typescript
// Define interfaces
interface UserRepository {
  findById(id: string): User | null;
}

interface Logger {
  log(message: string): void;
}

// Concrete implementations
class InMemoryUserRepository implements UserRepository {
  private users = new Map<string, User>();

  findById(id: string): User | null {
    return this.users.get(id) || null;
  }

  addUser(user: User) {
    this.users.set(user.id, user);
  }
}

class ConsoleLogger implements Logger {
  log(message: string): void {
    console.log(`[LOG] ${message}`);
  }
}

// User model
class User {
  constructor(public id: string, public name: string) {}
}

// UserService depends on abstractions
class UserService {
  constructor(
    private userRepo: UserRepository,
    private logger: Logger
  ) {}

  getUser(id: string): User | null {
    this.logger.log(`Fetching user with ID: ${id}`);
    return this.userRepo.findById(id);
  }
}

// External Composition Root (DI Container)
class AppContainer {
  private static userRepo: UserRepository;
  private static logger: Logger;

  static init() {
    this.userRepo = new InMemoryUserRepository();
    this.logger = new ConsoleLogger();

    // Register users
    (this.userRepo as InMemoryUserRepository).addUser(
      new User("1", "Alice")
    );
  }

  static resolveUserService(): UserService {
    return new UserService(this.userRepo, this.logger);
  }
}

// Bootstrap the application
AppContainer.init();
const userService = AppContainer.resolveUserService();

// Use the service
const user = userService.getUser("1");
console.log(user?.name); // Output: "Alice"
```

> 🔁 **IoC Principle**: Instead of the `UserService` creating its dependencies, they are "injected" from the outside. This makes it easy to swap implementations (e.g., switch to a database-based repository during testing).

