## Implementing Type-Safe APIs

TypeScript excels at enforcing type safety across API boundaries. Let’s explore how to maintain that safety in REST, GraphQL, and gRPC.

### 1. Type-Safe REST APIs with Zod and Express

Use **Zod** for runtime validation that aligns with your TypeScript types. This ensures data integrity at the API boundary.

#### Example: REST API with Zod Validation

```typescript
import express from 'express';
import { z } from 'zod';

const app = express();
app.use(express.json());

const UserSchema = z.object({
  id: z.number(),
  name: z.string().min(2),
  email: z.string().email(),
});

type User = z.infer<typeof UserSchema>;

const users: User[] = [];

app.post('/users', (req, res) => {
  const result = UserSchema.safeParse(req.body);
  if (!result.success) {
    return res.status(400).json({ errors: result.error.flatten() });
  }

  users.push(result.data);
  res.status(201).json(result.data);
});

app.get('/users/:id', (req, res) => {
  const id = parseInt(req.params.id);
  const user = users.find(u => u.id === id);
  if (!user) return res.status(404).send('User not found');
  res.json(user);
});

app.listen(3000, () => console.log('Type-safe REST API running'));
```

- **Benefits**: Compile-time type hints + runtime validation.
- **Tools**: Zod, Yup, or json-schema-to-typescript.

---

### 2. Type-Safe GraphQL APIs with Apollo Server

GraphQL benefits enormously from static typing. Use **GraphQL Code Generator** to generate TypeScript types from your schema.

#### Example: GraphQL API with Codegen

```typescript
// schema.graphql
type User {
  id: ID!
  name: String!
  email: String!
}

type Query {
  users: [User!]!
  user(id: ID!): User
}

type Mutation {
  createUser(name: String!, email: String!): User!
}
```

Run the generator:
```bash
graphql-codegen generate
```

This creates `types.ts` with fully typed resolvers:

```typescript
// Generated types.ts
export type Maybe<T> = T | null;
export type InputMaybe<T> = Maybe<T>;
export type Exact<T extends { [key: string]: unknown }> = { [K in keyof T]: T[K] };
export type MakeOptional<T, K extends keyof T> = Omit<T, K> & { [SubKey in K]?: Maybe<T[SubKey]> };
export type MakeMaybe<T, K extends keyof T> = Omit<T, K> & { [SubKey in K]: Maybe<T[SubKey]> };

export type ResolverTypeWrapper<T> = Promise<T> | T;

export type ResolverWithResolve<TResult, TParent, TContext, TArgs> = {
  resolve: ResolverFn<TResult, TParent, TContext, TArgs>;
};
export type Resolver<TResult, TParent = {}, TContext = {}, TArgs = {}> = ResolverFn<TResult, TParent, TContext, TArgs> | ResolverWithResolve<TResult, TParent, TContext, TArgs>;

export type ResolverFn<TResult, TParent, TContext, TArgs> = (
  parent: TParent,
  args: TArgs,
  context: TContext,
  info: GraphQLResolveInfo
) => Promise<TResult> | TResult;
```

Implement the server with full type safety:

```typescript
import { ApolloServer } from 'apollo-server';
import { readFileSync } from 'fs';
import { resolvers } from './resolvers';

const typeDefs = readFileSync('./schema.graphql', 'utf8');

const server = new ApolloServer({
  typeDefs,
  resolvers,
});

server.listen().then(({ url }) => {
  console.log(`🚀 Server ready at ${url}`);
});
```

Now every resolver is type-checked against your GraphQL schema.

